<TITLE> Durables orders, Freddie Mac provide firm view </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW YORK, July 25 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - New orders for long-lasting US manufactured goods rose unexpectedly in June on a surge in defense orders, while a gauge of business investment was also higher than forecast in signs of economic resilience, a government report showed on Friday. The housing market also received a rare bit of good news, with mortgage finance giant Freddie Mac reporting its retained mortgage portfolio jumped by more than a 33 percent annual rate in June to about $792 billion. The pace at which Freddie Mac, and its larger counterpart Fannie Mae, expand their mortgage purchases is seen as critical at a time when the government is relying heavily on the two companies to stabilize the worst US housing market since the Great Depression. Data earlier in the day shed light on the depressed state of the housing market, with US home foreclosure filings up 14 percent in the second quarter, according to real estate data firm RealtyTrac. However, stocks rose as financial markets focused mostly on news that durable goods orders rose 0.8 percent in June, after a revised 0.1 percent gain in May. "This is the first really positive piece of data in the past couple of weeks," said James Demasi, chief fixed income strategist at Stifel Nicolaus & Co Inc in Baltimore. The prices of government bonds, which perform better during times of economic weakness, fell. The dollar rose against the yen and pared its losses against the euro after the durables news. The durables data helped take the sting out of the foreclusures figures. The rise in foreclosures was the eighth consecutive quarterly climb and more than doubled from the same period a year earlier. Meanwhile, Freddie Mac said delinquencies on bonds it holds and guarantees kept climbing in May, though markets paid more attention to the jump in its portfolio, which is seen as supportive for the moribund U.S. housing market. Investor concern has centered on whether Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae have sufficient capital 